.TH GC 3 "2026-04-29" "libgc 1.0" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
gc \- conservative garbage collector for C
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.B #include <gc.h>

.BI "void gc_init(void);"
.BI "void gc_dump_stats(void);"

.BI "void *gc_malloc(size_t " size ");"
.BI "void *gc_calloc(size_t " nmemb ", size_t " size ");"
.BI "void gc_free(void *" ptr ");"
.BI "void gc_collect(void);"

.BI "void gc_add_root(void *" ptr_addr ");"
.BI "void gc_remove_root(void *" ptr_addr ");"
.BI "void gc_root_cleanup(void **" ptr_addr ");"

.BI "gc_weak_ref_t *gc_make_weak(void *" obj ", void (*" on_clear ")(void *, void *), void *" user_data ");"
.BI "void *gc_weak_get(gc_weak_ref_t *" ref ");"
.BI "void gc_weak_free(gc_weak_ref_t *" ref ");"
.BI "void gc_register_finalizer(void *" obj ", void (*" finalizer ")(void *, void *), void *" user_data ");"

.BI "int gc_pthread_create(pthread_t *" thread ", const pthread_attr_t *" attr ", void *(*" start ")(void *), void *" arg ");"
.BI "int gc_pthread_join(pthread_t " thread ", void **" retval ");"
.BI "void gc_pthread_exit(void *" retval ");"
.BI "void gc_register_thread_stack(void *" stack_bottom ");"
.BI "void gc_unregister_thread(void);"

.BI "int gc_pthread_mutex_init(gc_mutex_t **" mutex ", const pthread_mutexattr_t *" attr ");"
.BI "int gc_pthread_mutex_lock(gc_mutex_t *" mutex ");"
.BI "int gc_pthread_mutex_unlock(gc_mutex_t *" mutex ");"
.BI "int gc_pthread_mutex_destroy(gc_mutex_t *" mutex ");"
.BI "int gc_pthread_cond_init(gc_cond_t **" cond ", const pthread_condattr_t *" attr ");"
.BI "int gc_pthread_cond_wait(gc_cond_t *" cond ", gc_mutex_t *" mutex ");"
.BI "int gc_pthread_cond_signal(gc_cond_t *" cond ");"
.BI "int gc_pthread_cond_broadcast(gc_cond_t *" cond ");"
.BI "int gc_pthread_cond_destroy(gc_cond_t *" cond ");"

.B typedef struct gc_exception gc_exception_t;
.BI "void gc_throw(int " code ");"

.BI "void gc_write_barrier(void *" container_or_field ", void *" val ");"
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B gc
library provides a conservative, stop-the-world, mark-and-sweep garbage
collector for C. It can be used as a drop-in replacement for
.BR malloc (3)
and
.BR calloc (3)
in both single-threaded and multi-threaded programs.

The collector is conservative: it treats any word-aligned value on the
stack, in registers, or in the data segment that points into a managed
heap block as a live reference. False positives are possible but rare
and do not compromise safety.

Multi-threading is supported via a stop-the-world mechanism using POSIX
signals. Threads created with
.BR gc_pthread_create (3)
are automatically registered and scanned.

The library also provides GC-aware replacements for
.BR setjmp (3)
/
.BR longjmp (3)
via a
.B try/throw/catch
macro system, as well as GC-managed mutex and condition variable
wrappers.

.SS Initialization and Statistics
The collector initializes itself automatically on the first call to
.BR gc_malloc ()
or
.BR gc_calloc ().
Explicit initialization via
.BR gc_init ()
is optional but harmless.

.BR gc_dump_stats ()
prints internal state (bytes allocated, number of blocks, threshold)
to
.IR stderr .

.SS Memory Allocation
.BR gc_malloc ()
allocates
.I size
bytes and returns a pointer to the memory. The memory is not initialized.

.BR gc_calloc ()
allocates space for
.I nmemb
elements of
.I size
bytes each, initializes the memory to zero, and returns a pointer.

.BR gc_free ()
is provided for compatibility but does nothing – the collector decides
when to reclaim memory.

.BR gc_collect ()
forces an immediate garbage collection cycle. All threads are paused,
roots are scanned, and unreachable blocks are freed.

.SS Precise Roots
By default, the collector scans the stack, registers, and data segment
conservatively. To guarantee that a particular pointer is treated as a
root (e.g., to overcome false negatives or for global variables in
dynamic libraries), use
.BR gc_add_root ().
The address of a pointer variable is passed; the pointer stored at that
address will be treated as a root. Use
.BR gc_remove_root ()
to cancel the protection.
The macro
.B GC_ROOT(type, name)
declares a pointer, registers it as a root, and arranges automatic
cleanup at scope exit (requires GCC or Clang).

.SS Finalizers and Weak References
.BR gc_register_finalizer ()
schedules a function to be called just before a GC-managed object is
freed.

.BR gc_make_weak ()
creates a weak reference to an object, allowing the user to check
whether the object is still alive without preventing its collection.
.BR gc_weak_get ()
returns the original pointer or
.I NULL
if the object has been collected. The reference must be destroyed with
.BR gc_weak_free ().

.SS Exception Handling
The library provides a simple
.B try/throw/catch
mechanism based on
.BR sigsetjmp (3)
/
.BR siglongjmp (3).
Each thread maintains its own exception context.

.RS
.TP
.B TRY
Begins a guarded block. Must be followed by a
.B CATCH
block.
.TP
.B CATCH
Handles exceptions thrown inside the preceding
.B TRY
block. The exception code is available in
.BR gc_current_exception->code .
.TP
.B THROW(code)
Jumps to the innermost
.B CATCH
with the given code.
.TP
.B END_TRY
Placed after the
.B CATCH
block to clean up the environment.
.RE

.SS Thread Support
.BR gc_pthread_create ()
is a wrapper around
.BR pthread_create (3)
that registers the new thread with the collector.

.BR gc_pthread_join ()
is equivalent to
.BR pthread_join (3).

.BR gc_pthread_exit ()
unregisters the calling thread and then calls
.BR pthread_exit (3).

.BR gc_register_thread_stack ()
and
.BR gc_unregister_thread ()
allow manual registration of threads created by other means.

.SS Synchronization Primitives
.B gc_mutex_t
and
.B gc_cond_t
are either GC-managed structures (when
.B GC_FINALIZING
is enabled) or simple typedefs to the system types (otherwise).
In the GC-managed case they are allocated in GC memory and carry
finalizers that destroy the underlying pthread objects automatically.
Otherwise they behave exactly like standard
.BR pthread_mutex_t
/
.BR pthread_cond_t .

.SS Write Barrier (Incremental Marking)
When incremental marking is enabled
.RB ( GC_INCREMENTAL " = 1),"
the mutator must inform the collector of pointer updates to prevent
the lost-object problem. The macro
.B GC_WRITE_BARRIER(src, val)
should be called before storing a new pointer into an object.
A convenience macro
.B GC_ASSIGN_PTR(lhs, rhs)
performs the write barrier and the assignment in one step.

.SH RETURN VALUES
.BR gc_malloc ()
and
.BR gc_calloc ()
return a pointer to the allocated memory, or
.I NULL
if the request cannot be satisfied.

.BR gc_make_weak ()
returns a handle, or
.I NULL
on failure.

.BR gc_pthread_create ()
and
.BR gc_pthread_join ()
return 0 on success or an error code on failure.
Synchronization init functions return 0 or an error code.

.BR gc_throw ()
does not return.

.SH NOTES
The collector currently relies on Linux-specific features:
.IR /proc/self/maps
for stack detection,
.BR getcontext (3)
for register snapshots, and
.B SIGUSR1 / SIGUSR2
for stop-the-world synchronization. Porting to other operating systems
requires adapting these parts.

By default, a collection is triggered when the total allocated bytes
exceed 4 MiB. This threshold grows dynamically if memory pressure
remains high after a collection.

